        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our correlator configuration is driven primarily by the need to detect HDO at the level of VSMOW (HDO/H2O = 3x10^-4) in 
absorption against the dust continuum.  While our stated peak flux depth is 19 mJy and we formally request 9 mJy 
sensitivity (0.157 km/s spectral resolution), this value is considered to be the minimum depth of the absorption (see 
Science Justification text for further details).  We add that 19 mJy is only valid for a maximally broad absorption 
line (4.7 km/s).  In this case we can use channel averaging to readily gain a factor of 5 in sensitivity, thus guaranteeing 
a 10 sigma detection on even a shallow line.  The relatively high requested spectral resolution is set by the need to 
use the line widths differentiate between absorption from the envelope (1 km/s) and from the disk (&gt;2-5 km/s).  If the 
line is narrow, the line center optical depth grows very quickly and can be as much as tau_HDO~6 or higher, or ~ 300 mJy 
(30 sigma). However we remain conservative for our requested sensitiviy to ensure a detection.  We further emphasize that 
if HDO is not detected the D/H ratio in water is below VSMOW (which is in itself a very compelling result regarding the 
origin of HDO formation in disks versus the ISM).  

We do not aim to image the HDO, but rather take advantage of ALMA's frequency and sensitivity capabilities. We have 
requested the resolution of the most compact configuration for this spectral setting, 0.8'', which will help with 
the phase stability of the observations.

In addition to the HDO baseband, we have added additional basebands that cover related science goals.  We target a nearby 
low-energy line of D2O and CH3OH, both of which were selected to maximize the chance of catching these lines 
in absorption by targeting transitions specifically with lower state energies below 50 K. We have a second band targeting
another low-energy methanol line (3_30-3_-22) with the same purpose of catching photodesorbed ices in absorption, 
one of the most sensitive ways to measure abundances of rare species.  

The continuum at 464 GHz is estimated from the detailed fitting of Isella et al. 2009 who measured a 1.3mm flux
of 227 mJy in a 0.63 x 0.38 beam. From these observations which are slightly smaller than the requested beam, extrapolating 
from RY Tau's SED slope, F \propto nu^-2.5, we calculate the continuum flux to be ~ 1.3 Jy.  If the dust emitting area
is somewhat smaller, 0.3'', the continuum flux may be as low as 0.79 Jy. We use the latter to determine the expected 
depth of the absorption but also emphasize that a brighter continuum makes for a deeper absorption line without changing
the line to continuum ratio.  We emphasize that smallest line to continuum ratio in the broad-absorption scenario is
still better than 0.025, well within the limit of 1/500=0.002 for Band 8 as specified in the Cycle 2 Proposers Guide
(Appendix 8.1).

The main purpose of this proposal is to use absorption against the dusty submillimeter continuum to measure sensitive
abundances of species which are otherwise very difficult to observe.  This is only possible in inclined (i~60-70deg) 
disks, such as RY Tau.  Such observations absolutely require the high sensitivity and frequency coverage afforded by 
ALMA and are otherwise not possible.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
